  "texts": [
    "it has full min-entropy H ∞ (Y) = k 2) and c ∈ {0, 1} n 2 -k 2 be a fixed string, e.g.1, k 1, n 2, k 2, m, ϵ)-two- source randomness extractor Ext 2 is a (n 1, k 1, n ′ 2 = k 2, k 2,{0} n 2 -k 2, with H ∞ (c) = 0.",
    "Define Y ′ as the concatenation of Y and c, Y ′ = [Y, c], which has min-entropy H ∞ (Y ′) = H ∞ ([Y, c]) = H ∞ (Y) = k 2.Since Y ′ is a random variable with minentropy k 2 and length n 2, it can be used as the second input to any (n 1, k 1, n 2, k 2, m, ϵ)-two-source extractor Ext 2 (X, Y ′).",
    "Therefore, Ext 2 (X, Y ′) can be understood as a seeded extractor Ext s (X, Y), constructed by first concatenating the seed Y with a fixed string of bits then applying Ext 2.",
    "In other words,Ext s (X, Y) = Ext 2 (X, [Y, c]) = Ext 2 (X, Y ′).This theorem is useful when a seed is too short to be used in a seeded extractor for a given weak input.",
    "For example, consider a seed Y of length n 2 and a weak input X ∈ {0, 1} n 1 with n 1 > n 2."
  ]
